        <p>GHA Sun = <span class="value">${gha.toFixed(4)}°</span> (from almanac)</p>
        <hr>
        <p><span class="formula">Step 2:</span> Compute the fractional part of the Julian Date (day fraction).</p>
        <p>day fraction = (JD + 0.5) - floor(JD + 0.5)</p>
        <p>JD + 0.5 = ${(JD + 0.5).toFixed(5)}</p>
        <p>floor(JD + 0.5) = ${Math.floor(JD + 0.5)}</p>
        <p>day fraction = <span class="value">${dayfraction.toFixed(6)}</span></p>
        <hr>
        <p><span class="formula">Step 3:</span> Apply the formula: EOT (minutes) = 4 × GHA + 720 - 1440 × (day fraction)</p>
        <p>EOT (minutes) = 4 × ${gha.toFixed(4)} + 720 - 1440 × ${dayfraction.toFixed(6)}</p>
        <p>= ${(4*gha).toFixed(2)} + 720 - ${(1440*dayfraction).toFixed(2)}</p>
        <p>= <span class="value">${(4*gha + 720 - 1440*dayfraction).toFixed(2)} minutes</span></p>
        <hr>
        <p><span class="formula">Step 4:</span> Normalize to the range [-20, 20] minutes (as per original almanac).</p>
        <p>If the value is greater than 20, subtract 1440. If less than -20, add 1440.</p>
        <p>Here, the value is ${(4*gha + 720 - 1440*dayfraction).toFixed(2)} minutes.</p>
        <p>After normalization: <span class="value">${eot_minutes_calc.toFixed(2)} minutes</span></p>
        <hr>
        <p><span class="formula">Step 5:</span> Convert to hours (1 hour = 60 minutes).</p>
        <p>EOT (hours) = ${eot_minutes_calc.toFixed(2)} / 60 = <span class="value">${eot_hours_calc.toFixed(4)} h</span></p>
        <hr>
        <p><span class="formula">Final EOT:</span> <strong>${formatTimePrecise(eot)}</strong></p>
    `;
